A rough model you could have for the crypto credit crisis of 2022 is:
=09Everything was=C2=A0real, real rickety.=09All of the big serious players=
 could see that everything was rickety.=09This created obvious economic opp=
ortunities: Pick a rickety thing, bet on it collapsing, give it a gentle po=
ke, watch it collapse=C2=A0and collect your winnings.=09These opportunities=
 were tempting: If you were a big serious player, you could see the opportu=
nities, and you could sort of do the math on a napkin of how much money you=
=E2=80=99d make from a little poking.=09But=C2=A0everything=C2=A0was real, =
real rickety, including you. The big serious players in crypto were themsel=
ves opaque, levered, risk-loving and rickety.=09If you poked something else=
 and it collapsed, that would undermine confidence in crypto generally, and=
 the main thing keeping=C2=A0your=C2=A0project going was confidence in cryp=
to generally.=09Also the people whose project you poked might want revenge,=
 so they might poke you back.

One way to put this is that big serious players in crypto are long crypto v=
olatility at a small scale, but short crypto volatility at a large scale.
  [1]
=C2=A0At the level of napkin math, you could say =E2=80=9Cif Thing X goes d=
own, I will make $200 million, and I would like to make $200 million=E2=80=
=9D; more volatility means more trades. But at a more conceptual level, if =
Thing X goes down, that increases the chances that you will also go down. I=
f Thing X goes down by 50%, you make money. If Thing X goes down by 100%, y=
ou go bankrupt and become an international fugitive. You are long a  put sp=
read I guess.=C2=A0
Another way to put this is=C2=A0that there was, in crypto, a=C2=A0sort of  =
 half-understood imperfect equilibrium of mutually assured destruction: If =
everyone joined together to generously praise each other=E2=80=99s projects=
, they would bolster overall confidence in the crypto financial system, and=
 all of their projects would attract investors and do well. If one person s=
aid =E2=80=9Cnah those other projects are frauds,=E2=80=9D the other projec=
ts would collapse, but so would that guy=E2=80=99s project. But nobody knew=
 for sure exactly what the limits were, and there were temptations to cheat=
.
Another way to put it is, like, =E2=80=9C(3, 3)=E2=80=9D? One amazing crypt=
o project=C2=A0was (is, I guess)  OlympusDAO, whose basic premise was=C2=A0=
that if everyone bought its tokens and didn=E2=80=99t sell them, then every=
one would make money =E2=80=94=C2=A0whereas if you sold the tokens, you wou=
ld lose money (because the tokens would go down as you sold them) and so wo=
uld everyone else. In the glory days,  Olympus enthusiasts=C2=A0dressed up =
this insight in the notation=C2=A0of game theory:=C2=A0=E2=80=9C(3, 3)=E2=
=80=9D was their way of saying that if everyone buys it it will go up, whil=
e =E2=80=9C(-3, -3)=E2=80=9D means that if everyone sells it it will go dow=
n.
When I first found out about Olympus, and this notation, and what it meant,=
 I laughed really hard for a long time. What a trivial point, I thought. Bu=
t after the last few months I have developed a certain respect for it. In a=
 sense the game theory of crypto is obvious, but Olympus was right to=C2=A0=
emphasize it. This idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cif everyone cooperates, we=
=E2=80=99ll all get richer, but if people defect it will collapse=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0might be close to the core of crypto.
Anyway the New York Times  reported last week:

Federal prosecutors are investigating whether FTX=E2=80=99s founder, Sam Ba=
nkman-Fried, manipulated the market for two cryptocurrencies this past spri=
ng, leading to their collapse and creating a domino effect that eventually =
caused the implosion of his own cryptocurrency exchange last month, accordi=
ng to two people with knowledge of the matter.
U.S. prosecutors in Manhattan are examining the possibility that Mr. Bankma=
n-Fried steered the prices of two interlinked currencies, TerraUSD and Luna=
, to benefit the entities he controlled, including FTX and Alameda Research=
, a hedge fund he co-founded and owned, the people said.
The investigation is in its early stages, and it is not clear whether prose=
cutors have determined any wrongdoing by Mr. Bankman-Fried, or when they be=
gan looking at the TerraUSD and Luna trades. =E2=80=A6
In May, major cryptocurrency market makers =E2=80=94 exchanges or individua=
ls who arrange for buyers and sellers to be matched =E2=80=94 noticed a flo=
od of =E2=80=9Csell=E2=80=9D orders coming in for TerraUSD, said one person=
 with knowledge of the market activity. The orders were in small denominati=
ons, but they were placed very quickly, the person said. ...
The exact causes of the collapse of the two cryptocurrencies remain unclear=
. However, the bulk of the sell orders for TerraUSD appeared to be coming f=
rom one place: Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s cryptocurrency trading firm, whi=
ch also placed a big bet on the price of Luna falling, according to the per=
son with knowledge of the market activity.
Had the trade gone as expected, the price declines in Luna could have yield=
ed a fat profit. Instead, the bottom fell out of the entire TerraUSD-Luna e=
cosystem. The collapse caused more trouble in the cryptocurrency industry, =
sending several prominent companies into bankruptcy and erasing about $1 tr=
illion in value from the crypto market.
The ripple effects from the Luna crash ultimately contributed to the collap=
se of Mr. Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s business empire. In November, Caroline El=
lison, the chief executive of Alameda, told staff that loans to Alameda wer=
e recalled as a result of the market chaos unleashed by the crash, accordin=
g to a person familiar with the matter. But the funds that Alameda had borr=
owed were no longer easily available, Ms. Ellison told the staff, so the co=
mpany used FTX customer funds to make the payments.

One technical version of this story would be that Alameda was both a direct=
ional prop trading firm and a big market maker on FTX. In its prop business=
, it (perhaps) had a big bet against Luna, which made money as Luna went do=
wn. In its market-making business, it served as a sort of buyer of last res=
ort on FTX, and as people dumped Luna it ended up buying their Luna. It cou=
ld have been short Luna at the start of the collapse but long Luna by the m=
iddle of the collapse, meaning that it lost a lot of money by the end of th=
e collapse. It was long Luna volatility at a small scale, but short Luna vo=
latility on a large scale. There is   some speculation that that=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0what happened.
But a less technical version of the story would be that Alameda might have =
made or lost money on the Luna trade, but what ultimately sunk Alameda and =
FTX was not how much money they made or lost on any particular trades. What=
 sunk them was some combination of (1) a gigantic hole in their balance she=
ets, (2) an attempt to cover over that hole with   a thin layer of magic-be=
an tokens that FTX had made up and that it ascribed enormous value to, and =
(3) people noticing. If Luna had not collapsed, FTX=E2=80=99s magic-bean to=
kens might have held their value better, people might not have noticed the =
problems, no one would have withdrawn their money and the whole thing could=
 have kept going.
We   talked last week about Kyle Davies=E2=80=99s revealing interview with =
Hugh Hendry about how Three Arrows Capital, or 3AC, collapsed. Davies and h=
is co-founder Su Zhu ran 3AC, a prop trading firm much like Alameda; they w=
ere long Luna and lost money on the collapse.  Part II of that interview wa=
s posted on Friday, and in it Davies says casually that 3AC was surprised b=
y the Luna collapse, but lost only $200 million on it, not a huge hit compa=
red to 3AC=E2=80=99s billions under management. Luna is not what blew up 3A=
C. But after the Luna collapse, confidence in crypto financial firms collap=
sed, and so lenders recalled loans from firms like 3AC and Alameda. That is=
=C2=A0also=C2=A0not what blew up 3AC, in Davies=E2=80=99s telling: 3AC had =
enough money to repay its lenders. What blew up 3AC was the third-order eff=
ect: Lenders recalled loans from crypto hedge funds, and so all the popular=
 crypto hedge fund trades collapsed as those funds were forced to sell; 3AC=
 was in all the popular crypto hedge fund trades and lost money on all of t=
hem, and then it ran out of money to pay its lenders. If 3AC had been=C2=A0=
short Luna, it might have made $200 million on that trade, but the $200 mil=
lion would not have helped that much. The big problem was not any particula=
r trade, but the collapse of the whole=C2=A0ecosystem in which everyone was=
 making money doing the same trades.
It is a funny interview because Davies says =E2=80=9Cthere were numerous bl=
ack swans that happened=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0some of which were really quite=
 extreme, I thought,=E2=80=9D and you can sort of watch Hendry=E2=80=99s he=
ad explode. For one thing, that is an abuse of terminology: Black swans are=
 supposed to be rare and extreme, and if you are talking about =E2=80=9Cnum=
erous black swans=E2=80=9D then you have made errors both of language and o=
f risk management.
Also, though =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean the whole point of the =E2=80=9Cblack sw=
an=E2=80=9D metaphor is that if you go around for hundreds of years only se=
eing white swans, you are entitled to assume that all swans are white, and =
then when you travel to another continent and you see a black swan you are =
entitled to feel surprised. If you go around in=C2=A0your backyard for 20 m=
inutes only seeing gray squirrels, and then you go to your front yard and=
=C2=A0see a black squirrel, you will feel less surprised.=C2=A0You just did=
 not have that much data on which to form a conclusion like =E2=80=9Call sq=
uirrels are gray.=E2=80=9D Hendry says to Davies: =E2=80=9CThe market hadn=
=E2=80=99t existed for more than 10 years or so. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0There=E2=80=
=99s no observation set; everything is risk.=E2=80=9D It is just weird to b=
e surprised that Luna collapsed. Luna=E2=80=99s existence was a blip;  its =
TerraUSD stablecoin came into existence in 2020, maintained its value for a=
 little while, and then fell nearly to zero. Its median price over any five=
-year period was zero. The black swan was when it was worth $1. The   colla=
pse of an algorithmic stablecoin is one of the least surprising events in t=
he world, right up there with =E2=80=9Ca crypto exchange steals or loses it=
s customers=E2=80=99 money.=E2=80=9D
This is the problem with my rough model of the crypto credit crisis of 2022=
. It=E2=80=99s easy for me now to say =E2=80=9Ceverything was real, real ri=
ckety,=E2=80=9D after Luna and 3AC and Celsius and Voyager and BlockFi and =
FTX and Alameda all blew up, and it=E2=80=99s certainly possible that a lot=
 of the important players knew the problems=C2=A0and hastened the explosion=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Alameda shorted Luna, or that Binance=E2=80=99s Chang=
peng Zhao   did some tweets=C2=A0that destroyed FTX. But a real model would=
 also take into account Davies=E2=80=99s childlike wonder that something as=
 stable as Luna could collapse overnight. What is incredible about the cryp=
to credit crisis is that, in the spring of=C2=A02022, things like Luna and =
3AC and FTX looked like established institutions, such that their collapse =
could look like black swan events. What is incredible is that confidence in=
 those institutions grew so fast and, for a little while, looked so robust.=
 They came from nothing, and they quickly returned to nothing, and when you=
   look at the   postmortems it is a little hard to understand why they eve=
r inspired any confidence. But they did, and for a while that was what made=
 them valuable.

